<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Sees NATO Action `Inevitable' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0103192494 Rome RAI Uno Television Network in Italian 1700 
GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0103192494 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome RAI Uno Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] During a visit to the Rivolto air base, in 
Friuli, Defense Minister Fabio Fabbri spoke about the shooting 
down of the Serb planes and diplomatic reactions to the 
incident, especially from Russia. Tino Zava reports. 
  [Tino Zava, voice over video] NATO is not a rusty machine -- 
on the contrary, it is an organization capable of acting with 
great timeliness and efficiency. According to Defense Minister 
Fabio Fabbri, this is demonstrated by what happened in Bosnia 
yesterday, where NATO and the United Nations had much of their 
credibility at stake. He said that the incident at Banja Luka 
was sad but inevitable. [passage omitted] 
  Is there any possibility of reprisals against Italy, where 
the U.S. F-16's set out from? Fabbri promised that we would 
monitor the situation closely. 
  [Fabbri] The protective shield created by NATO is able to 
warn us of any movement from that territory that might 
constitute a threat against our territory. 
  [Zava] Fabbri praised Russia's stance over the Banja Luka 
incident, and then spoke about Italy's new defense plan. There 
will be more fighter planes rather than missiles. 

</TEXT>

