<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rifkind Cautions Serbs Against Revenge </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0103201094 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1903 GMT 1 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0103201094 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Paul Edwards] </F>
  [Text] Defence Secretary Malcolm Rifkind today warned the 
Serbs against any retaliatory action following the shooting down 
of four of their attack aircraft. 
  Mr Rifkind said the action against the aircraft was sad but 
the UN Security Council had given a clear warning that any use 
of fixed wing aircraft for aggressive purposes would result in 
that action. 
  Asked if he was concerned at any Serbian response, he 
replied: "One has always been conscious of the fact that people 
might be tempted to make any retaliatory incidents. 
  ``I think they should take into account that the United 
Nations forces in general, and the British forces in particular, 
have the means and military assets to defend themselves and 
would have the full support of the British Government and the UN 
as a whole if they needed to use them.'' 
  Mr Rifkind was visiting the Royal Navy's weapons engineering 
shore training establishment, HMS Collingwood, at Fareham, 
Hampshire. Earlier, at the Portsmouth naval base, he met 
Admiral Sir John Kerr, Commander in Chief Naval Home Command, 
and other senior officers. 

</TEXT>

