<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Not Putting Pressure on Croatia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0203200994 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1844 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0203200994 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Goettingen (DDP/ADN) -- The Society for Threatened 
Peoples (GfbV) has accused Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel of 
being partially responsible for the war crimes Croatians carried 
out in Bosnia-Herzegovina. Tilman Zuelch, the head of the 
society, said today that although Kinkel had been fully aware of 
the Croatian human rights violations and war crimes, he had not 
made any serious efforts to put pressure of the Croatian 
Government. 
  Zuelch was speaking in connection with a GfbV report 
submitted to the UN Human Rights Commission in Geneva on 
Croatian human rights violations against the civilian population 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina. The report accuses Croatian troops in 
particular of confining and starving 55,000 Muslim deportees and 
displaced persons in the town of Mostar for months, of razing 
towns through large-scale bombardment, and of killing hundreds 
of civilians. 

</TEXT>

