<H3> <TI>   Aristide `Satisfied' France Not To Support U.S. Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0203145894 Paris LE QUOTIDIEN DE PARIS in French 2 Mar 94 
p 18 </F>

<F P=103> BR0203145894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE QUOTIDIEN DE PARIS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Haiti: Aristide in Paris"] </F>
  [Text] Father Jean-Bertrand Aristide, Haiti's president in 
exile, was welcomed by President Mitterrand at the Elysee 
yesterday with all the honors due a chief of state. The talks 
between the two men lasted 20 minutes. Mr. Aristide said that 
he was "very satisfied" with the attitude adopted by France, 
which promised, according to him, that it would "not support" a 
new plan backed by Washington for the settlement of the crisis 
in Haiti. This plan provides for the anticipated retirement of 
General Raoul Cedras, Haitian Armed Forces chief of staff, and 
the creation of a new government, but does not guarantee the 
return of President Aristide. 

</TEXT>

