<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry on Russian Forces in Azerbaijan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0203202794 Ankara ANATOLIA in Turkish 1630 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0203202794 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Regarding claims that Russia has been 
dispatching units to establish security zones in Azerbaijan, 
Turkey has stated that should peace forces be required in 
Azerbaijan, it should be done within the framework of the CSCE 
principles which stipulate that these units be multinational. 
  Foreign Ministry Deputy Spokesman Ferhat Ataman, at his 
weekly news conference, indicated that there was no information 
regarding Russian soldiers being sent to Azerbaijan, adding that 
the sending of peace forces to the CSCE countries was determined 
at the CSCE Council of Ministers meeting in Rome. [passage 
omitted] 
  Ataman further stated that they received reports regarding a 
ceasefire in Azerbaijan but that it was not comprehensive and 
recalled that Turkey stressed that the ceasefire, on its own, is 
not sufficient to solve the issue. 
  Ataman concluded by saying that the ceasefire will be 
significant only if the Armenians withdraw from the territories 
they occupy and enable the refugees to return. 

</TEXT>

