<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Offers No Information on PKK Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0203174594 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1500 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0203174594 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, Mar. 2 (A.A.) -- Foreign Ministry officials 
said on Wednesday [2 March] that they have not received any 
information from Russia concerning a meeting in Moscow of the 
supporters of PKK [Workers Party of Kurdistan], the separatist 
terrorist organization. 
  Foreign Ministry Deputy Spokesman Ferhat Ataman told a 
weekly 
news conference that the Ministry asked for information on the 
issue. "However, Russia has yet to inform us on the meeting," 
Ataman said. Ataman said Foreign Ministry official Bilgin Unan, 
who is currently in Russia for official talks, could bring the 
issue up. 
  A conference was held in Moscow last month by a number of 
organizations which are believed to have ties with the 
separatist terrorist organization. Russian Minister Valerie 
Samsurov [name and title as received] was in attendance at the 
Moscow meeting of the PKK supporters. 
  Russian Ambassador to Turkey Albert Chernyshev was summoned 
to the Foreign Ministry and was asked to inquire about the 
meeting. He assured Foreign Ministry officials that there has 
been no change in his country's policy. 
  Ataman said a delegation from the Foreign Ministry arrived 
in 
Moscow on Tuesday to discuss relations between Turkey and Russia. 

</TEXT>

