<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Supports Middle East Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0203153594 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1445 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0203153594 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, Mar. 2 (A.A.) -- Turkey said on Wednesday 
[2 March] that it supported the continuation of the Middle East 
peace talks. Foreign Ministry Deputy Spokesman Ferhat Ataman 
told a press conference that the massacre of 63 Palestinians in 
Hebron's Ibrahim Mosque by a fanatic Jewish settler should not 
hinder the peace process. Ataman said such "regrettable" 
incidents showed that the peace process was still in a sensitive 
and critical point. 
  Ataman recalled that Israel proposed several measures to 
prevent such incidents from happening again, however the 
Palestinian people found them inadequate. 
  After the incident President Suleyman Demirel called 
Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat [title as received] and 
expressed his condolences over the massacre saying, "I am 
shocked to hear the news regarding the brutal attack perpetrated 
against innocent Palestinians praying in the Mosque." Demirel 
also said Turkey was ready to do its utmost if help is demanded 
to further the Middle East peace process. 

</TEXT>

