<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   FYROM Embargo Being Implemented `Faithfully' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0203132294 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1230 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0203132294 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Commenting on Skopjean press reports that a truck 
crossed the Greek border yesterday carrying industrial material, 
Government Spokesman Evangelos Venizelos said the embargo 
against Skopje [The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia--FYROM] is being implemented faithfully. He said the 
measures have not been eased, adding that food and medicines as 
part of humanitarian aid are the only exception. 
  Venizelos described the delay in the United States 
establishing diplomatic relations with Skopje as a positive 
element. Asked to comment on yesterday's remarks by U.S. 
Secretary of State Warren Christopher urging all the countries 
in the region to show an interest in Macedonia, as he referred 
to Skopje, the spokesman said: Greece is the friendliest 
country toward Skopje and is interested in its viability and 
development. But [FYROM President Kiro] Gligorov's continuing 
intransigence does not help it. 
  Referring to an interview with Gligorov in an Athens 
newspaper [paper not identified] today, Venizelos said he saw 
some calm, moderate statements. He added that despite the 
carefully expressed views, the Skopjean president does not 
deviate from his basic position. Venizelos said: With careful 
political dialogue, Gligorov appears as a victim. But the 
international community must also realize that Greece took the 
counter measures because of Skopje's provocative and 
untrustworthy behavior. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

