<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Belarus Seeks Aid Cleaning Nuclear Fallout </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0303212994 Hamburg DPA in German 1615 GMT 3 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0303212994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- Help for the scrapping of about 2,00 
tanks and for coping with the radiation consequences of the 
Chernobyl reactor accident were the central topics during the 
first visit by Belarusian Foreign Minister Petr Kravchanka to 
his counterpart Klaus Kinkel on Thursday [3 March]. In addition 
to a cultural agreement, the ministers also signed a framework 
agreement for the "promotion of cooperation in alleviating the 
consequences of the Chernobyl nuclear accident." 
  According to the Foreign Ministry, Kinkel stressed Germany's 
interest in stability in Belarus and recommended participation 
in NATO's Partnership for Peace, which he called an important 
building block for an all-European security architecture. At a 
subsequent press conference, Kravchanka was restrained in his 
comments and only called the offer "interesting." The cutting 
off of gas supplies by Russia is not a political problem, but 
only due to bureaucratic "problems of accounting," Kravchanka 
said. 
  In the reduction of conventional armament, Belarus has 
become 
a collection pond of about 2,000 tanks so far, the scrapping of 
which it cannot carry out on its own. It asked France, Great 
Britain, and Germany for financial and technological aid. 
Belarus' greatest tragedy is, however, still the Ukrainian 
Chernobyl disaster of 1986. Almost the entire territory was 
contaminated by the radioactive fall-out, which moved northwest. 
An increasing number of lethal cases of thyroid cancer in 
children has given Belarus a sad front ranking in the 
international statistics, Kravchanka stated. 

</TEXT>

