<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Industry Expects `New Impulses' for Exports to EU </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0203162794 Hamburg DPA in German 1327 GMT 2 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0203162794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cologne/Saarbruecken (DPA) -- The leading 
associations of the Germany industry have described the 
enlargement of the European Union [EU] by Sweden, Finland, and 
Austria as a positive signal for enterprises in Germany. The 
Federal Association of German Wholesale and Foreign Trade (BGA) 
expects new jobs and lower prices from the enlargement of the 
European Union. 
  The accession of the three countries will provide new 
impulses to the German export economy, BGA Executive Director 
Peter Spary said. "We are now even bigger than the North 
American free trade zone NAFTA [North American Free Trade 
Agreement]," Spary said on Saarland radio. The German consumers 
can also be happy about the enlargement: "Competition in 
wholesale and foreign trade will reduce prices even further." 
  The Federal Association of German Industry [BDI] in Cologne 
stated that the Germany industry was relieved that the 
membership negotiations with Sweden, Finland, and Austria were 
concluded on time and is hoping that agreement with Norway will 
follow in a few days. 
  For the German industry, the enlargement of the European 
Union by EFTA [European Free Trade Association] countries has 
always been at the top of its European objectives list. "The 
intensive trade and investment relations with this area speak 
for enlargement as do the democratic and liberal traditions of 
these countries." The industry is hoping that with their 
accession, the advocates of a cosmopolitan policy and a policy 
of the market economy by the European Union will receive further 
support. 

</TEXT>

