<H3> <TI>   Cabinet Approves European-U.S. Uranium Plant Project </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0203204694 Hamburg DPA in German 1716 GMT 2 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0203204694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- The Federal Cabinet on Wednesday [2 
March] adopted a government agreement for approving a 
European-U.S. joint venture for the construction of a uranium 
enrichment plant in the United States. This facility is to be 
built and operated by private companies. According to a 
government spokesman, the plant is supposed to be built in 
Louisiana. 
  The German-British-Dutch company Urenco is involved in the 
project. The goal is to slightly enrich uranium in the plant by 
using the so-called gas-ultracentrifuge method, which is already 
being applied by Urenco. The fuel rods are intended for 
light-water nuclear power plants on the U.S. market. 
  The framework agreement adopted by the Cabinet ensures that 
the operation of the facility will observe the nuclear 
nonproliferation treaty on the nonproliferation of weapons-grade 
material and that the safety measures of the International 
Atomic Energy Agency are taken into consideration. According to 
the spokesman, the facility is exclusively intended for the 
peaceful use of nuclear material. 

</TEXT>

