<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Expansion of Money Supply Speeds Up `Suprisingly' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0203104494 Hamburg DPA in German 0945 GMT 2 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0203104494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Frankfurt/Main (DPA) -- The expansion of the money 
supply surprisingly sped up at the beginning of the year. On 
Wednesday [2 March], the German Bundesbank stated that the M3 
money supply in January -- after it was seasonally adjusted -- 
was superior to the average level of the fourth quarter 1993 
with an annual rate of 20.6 percent. 
  Apart from the notes and coins in circulation, the money 
supply M3 also includes sight deposits, time deposits with 
maturities of less than four years, and savings deposits. 
According to the Bundesbank, all these components grew rapidly 
in January. "The pace of expansion was strongest for sight 
deposits." For 1994, the Bundesbank is seeking a monetary 
increase between 4 and 6 percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

