<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Steinmetz' Role in RAF Not Clarified by Bundestag </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0203201294 Hamburg DPA in German 1722 GMT 2 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0203201294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- The role of liaison man Klaus 
Steinmetz, who was uncovered during the antiterrorism operation 
in Bad Kleinen, in the Red Army Faction (RAF) has not been 
finally clarified by the Bundestag's Parliamentary Control 
Committee. There are also still "incongruities" concerning his 
relationship with the Rhineland-Palatinate Office for the 
Protection of the Constitution, participants revealed after a 
meeting of the Committee in Bonn on Wednesday [2 March]. 
  Thus, it is unclear what Steinmetz did for the authority and 
why the Land Office for the Protection of the Constitution did 
not tell the Federal Government earlier about the liaison man, 
who was allegedly infiltrated in the RAF command echelon, it was 
said. It was stressed that the suspension of the criminal 
proceedings against Steinmetz, which was ordered by the chief 
federal prosecutor's office, is only a temporary measure. 
Further insights might be gained from the criminal proceedings 
against Birgit Hogefeld, who was arrested in Bad Kleinen. 

</TEXT>

