<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Andreatta Discusses Bosnian Conflict With Stoltenberg </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0303085194 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2059 GMT 2 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0303085194 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Andreatta Meets Stoltenberg"] </F>
  [Text] Rome, 2 Mar (ANSA) -- The preliminary understanding 
reached in Washington between Muslim and Croat authorities from 
the ex-Yugoslavia republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina and recent 
events in Bosnia were discussed here today by Foreign Minister 
Beniamino Andreatta and Thorvald Stoltenberg, one of the 
international mediators chairing the Geneva Conference on 
ex-Yugoslavia. 
  A statement issued by the Foreign Ministry said Andreatta 
and 
Stoltenberg expressed great satisfaction with the accord reached 
in Washington for the formation of a confederation in 
violence-torn Bosnia and view this as a positive turning point 
in the negotiating process. 
  Italy, the communique recalled, has actively favored 
rapprochement between Sarajevo and Zagreb and sought to further 
dialogue between Croatian President Franjo Tudjman and the 
Bosnian Muslim president, Alija Izetbegovic, at the time of a 
visit to Rome by Croatian Foreign Minister Mate Granic, on 
February 3, for talks with Andreatta. 
  The Italian minister, who has directly followed developments 
in this area through meetings and contacts with Croatian and 
Muslim authorities, agreed today with Stoltenberg on the point 
that the institutional framework now crystallizing between the 
two sides could become a fundamental stage for the settlement of 
the entire set of disputes pertaining to ex-Yugoslavia. 
  Andreatta and the international mediator also stressed the 
need to maintain the pace of political and diplomatic 
initiatives in the successive phases of the accord. For this 
purpose, greater commitment will be required to win a deeper 
involvement of Bosnian Serbs so as to move on to a global 
political solution to the conflict. 
  The importance of strengthening consultations among the 
European Union, the United States and Russia, for the purpose of 
consolidating the coordination of international actions, will 
also be indispensable for achieving results, within the 
framework of the Geneva Conference, acceptable to all sides, 
said the two men. 
  At the end of their meeting, Andreatta invited Stoltenberg 
to 
Trieste for a meeting of the Central European Initiative, 
scheduled for Friday [4 March] and Saturday. Expected for this 
assembly are the Bosnian and Croatian foreign ministers for 
discussion on the details of the accord reached today in 
Washington. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

