<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Prefers Political Progress, Not Ultimatum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0303150794 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1119 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0303150794 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Berlin (DDP/ADN) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus 
Kinkel does not want the example of the NATO ultimatum to be 
applied to other areas in Bosnia yet. In an interview with the 
television company `N-TV' in Berlin on Thursday [3 March], 
Kinkel came out against issuing such an ultimatum "without 
examination" and "automatically" for such cities as Tuzla and 
Bihac. Instead, the "new momentum" has to be used "to make 
political progress." 
  Kinkel nevertheless advocates linking the "political" and 
the 
"military" components. He argues for "tackling the individual 
crisis spots with this combination of the military and the 
political approaches, but above all with the political 
approach." In this way, an "overall solution" should be 
achieved "by a domino effect." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

