<F P=100> PORTUGAL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Cited on Lusaka Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0403001694 Lisbon RDP Antena 1 Radio Network in Portuguese 
2200 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0403001694 </F>
<F P=104>  Lisbon RDP Antena 1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Portuguese Minister of Foreign Affairs Durao Barroso 
is visiting South Africa, but is thinking about Angola. The 
foreign minister told us that the Lusaka agreement is 
technically ready, but it has not been signed yet because there 
is no political will: 
  [Begin recording] [Durao Barroso] From a technical point of 
view, the documents are at a rather advanced stage. I met 
moments ago with a representative of the negotiating team who 
confirmed that news. The fundamental problem is whether there 
is the will on either side for a true national reconciliation 
agreement to be signed. 
  [Correspondent Carlos Pacheco] But does this [the will] 
exist 
or not? 
  [Barroso] So far it has not existed. 
  [Pacheco] And, according to what you have just said, what 
will be the logical outcome of the Lusaka negotiations? 
  [Barroso] Well, a logical outcome would be a positive 
conclusion, but that will obviously be subject to a political 
rectification, at the highest level, from both sides. I cannot 
foresee it at the moment. 
  [Pacheco] Do the conditions exist for that to happen? 
  [Barroso] At the same time as there has been progress at the 
Lusaka talks, the fact is that the situation has been worsening 
on the ground. [end recording] 
  [Announcer] That was Portuguese Minister of Foreign Affairs 
Durao Barroso talking to our correspondent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

