<F P=101> Denmark </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Confident of Norwegian EU Membership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0303152694 Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE in Danish 2 Mar 
94 p 13 </F>

<F P=103> PM0303152694 </F>
<F P=104>  Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Danish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [RITZAUS BUREAU report: "Nyrup Rasmussen Confident of </F>
Norwegian Membership"] 
  [Excerpt] Copenhagen -- Prime Minister Poul Nyrup 
Rasmussen (Social Democratic Party) was happy when it was 
announced yesterday that Sweden had reached agreement with the 
EU [European Union] in its membership negotiations. It was a 
piece of good news that also boosted the prime minister's 
optimism about successfully concluding Norway's membership 
negotiations. 
  "This is pleasing. Now I hope we will see rapid progress and 
a solution for all four countries (Sweden, Finland, Norway, and 
Austria -- editorial note) within a few days. 
  ``It is of crucial importance that the negotiating tempo is 
maintained and that all four countries achieve a result. I 
believe that Norway will also achieve a solution,'' the prime 
minister said. 
  Shortly before, at his weekly meeting with the press at 
Christiansborg, he had stressed that it is of crucial importance 
that the negotiations should succeed. 
  "The words `collapse of the negotiations' do not exist in 
our 
dictionary. They will succeed. For the sake of the Nordic 
countries, for the sake of the EU, and against the background of 
the future enlargement negotiations with the countries of East 
Europe," he said. 
  The prime minister said that he would like to see more 
flexibility in the enlargement negotiations on the part of Spain. 
  "It is necessary that Spain too should understand the 
consideration that must be given to the Norwegian fish stocks. 
If the political will exists, the question can be resolved," 
the prime minister said. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

