<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Comments on Lifting of DEP Immunity </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0303161094 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1436 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0303161094 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, Mar. 3 (A.A.) -- State minister and 
government spokesman Yildirim Aktuna said today that the 
decision of Parliament to remove the political immunity of seven 
members of the Democracy Party (DEP) has eased the public 
conscience. 
  In a written statement, Aktuna said the important thing at 
this moment is to prevent certain DEP deputies from using their 
immunity as a shield and to pave way for independent justice. 
  Parliament removed the immunity of six DEP members Wednesday 
[3 March] and is set to remove the immunity of another three 
today. 
  "The members of Parliament will certainly act in line with 
the people's will," he said. "Certain DEP members had recently 
intensified their actions against the unity of the country." 
  He added that a recent statement of Hatip Dicle, who 
described the killing of five military cadets and the injuring 
of 26 by a separatist terrorist organization as "a normal action 
in war" had created deep resentment in society. 
  Aktuna added that the March 27 local polls will be conducted 
in a safe atmosphere. 
  The DEP, which held 13 seats in the 450-seat Parliament 
announced a week ago that it was withdrawing from the polls. 

</TEXT>

