<H3> <TI>   EU Broadcasters Complying With Program Regulations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0303170994 Paris AFP in English 1650 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0303170994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, March 3 (AFP) -- A controversial 1991 
European Union regulation that television channels must 
broadcast a majority of European programmes is being largely 
respected, the European Commission said here Thursday [3 March]. 
  It released a survey showing that 70 of 105 channels -- 66 
percent -- had obeyed the directive, which states that more than 
50 percent of programmes excluding sport and news must be 
provided by European producers. 
  Among those not meeting the directive, a Commission 
spokesman 
named several satellite channels in Britain and a cable channel 
in France. 
  The Commission is preparing a report on the directive and 
possible modifications before October this year. 

