<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Thousands' Demonstrate Against Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0303164994 Paris AFP in English 1629 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0303164994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Paris, March 3 (AFP) -- Thousands of students 
demonstrated here on Thursday [3 March] to demand that 
conservative Prime Minister Edouard Balladur drop plans to cut 
France's minimum legal wage for young people. 
  The university and high school students blocked the 
capital's 
Latin Quarter as police sealed off the nearby residence of the 
prime minister, where he was holding a roundtable meeting on 
employment with trade union leaders and employers' 
representatives. 
  The students shouted "Balladur, you've had it. The kids have 
taken to the streets." 
  Among them was the secretary general of the powerful 
communist-led CGT [General Labor Confederation] union, Louis 
Viannet, who walked out of the meeting with the prime minister 
after he had refused to withdraw his plan. 
  Also among the demonstrators were Communist Party leader 
Robert Hue and Socialist Party official Jean-Christophe 
Cambadelis. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

