<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Belgium's Claes, Mitterrand Discuss Bosnia, EU </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0303155594 Groot-Bijgaarden DE STANDAARD in Dutch 3 Mar 94 
p 4 </F>

<F P=103> BR0303155594 </F>
<F P=104>  Groot-Bijgaarden DE STANDAARD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed PVDM: "Willy Claes Paying Working Visit to </F>
Mitterand and Juppe"] 
  [Text] Paris -- "Europeans, Americans, and Russians should 
now get together in order to get new peace talks on Bosnia 
going. We must take advantage of the present opportunities." 
Foreign Minister Willy Claes reiterated this position in Paris 
yesterday, after meeting with President Francois Mitterrand and 
his colleague Alain Juppe. 
  Claes was in Paris on a working visit. He reported to his 
colleague Juppe on the talks on European Union [EU] enlargement. 
Both ministers also discussed the financing of the common 
foreign policy. Some members of the Union argue it should be 
financed by special contributions from the member states. 
"However, we can hardly develop a common policy, if, with every 
action, we must discuss who will pay what," Claes stated. 
  France has now suggested eastablishment of a fund which 
would 
be financed partly by Community funds and partly by member state 
contributions. "This seems to be a good working hypothesis," 
Claes said. 
  With Mitterrand, the Belgian minister talked mainly about 
the 
situation in Rwanda and Burundi, where he was on a visit last 
week, and about Zaire. 
  With his counterparts, Claes also made preparations for the 
Paris Conference. Last December's European Summit in Brussels 
adopted French Prime Minister Edouard Balladur's idea of a 
Security Pact in Europe. 
  Belgium fears that this conference might be pointless, 
unless 
one succeeds in getting countries such as Slovakia and Romania, 
which are showing little interest, around the table. The 
purpose of the conference, scheduled to start in Paris next 
April, is precisely to convice the countries of Central and East 
Europe, including Russia, to reach agreements concerning their 
borders and respect of minorities on their territories. 

</TEXT>

