<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Greek Minister Says EU To Present New Ideas on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0503153694 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1426 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0503153694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Cairo, March 5 (TANJUG) -- Greek Foreign Minister 
Karolos Papoulias said here on Saturday [5 March] the European 
Union would present new ideas on Bosnia-Herzegovina which would 
basically rely on its peace plan for that war-torn former 
Yugoslav republic. 
  Asked by TANJUG what the EU, which is currently chaired by 
Greece, planned to do following the U.S. initiative for a 
Moslem-Croat federation in Bosnia, Papoulias said Europe would 
come out with its own ideas on how to resolve the crisis. 
  Acting under strong pressure from Washington, Bosnian Moslem 
and Croat officials met in Washington on Tuesday to sign a 
preliminary deal on forming a binational federation, which would 
subsequently form confederate ties with neighbouring Croatia. 
  Washington's idea is to use the binational federation 
manoeuvre to enable the Moslems to preserve the integrity of 
Bosnia, expand the territory under their control, give them 
access to the sea and, finally, create a strong negotiating (and 
possibly military) bloc against the Serbs. 
  In Cairo, Papoulias met Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak for 
talks on various issues, including Bosnia-Herzegovina, but he 
did not elaborate on that point. 
  Egypt has cautiously welcomed the Moslem-Croat rapprochement 
under Washington's auspices, but the government-controlled press 
has been writing over the past few days the latest developments 
clearly indicate that Bosnia will be divided and that its days 
in the present shape are numbered. 
  Bosnian Serbs, who were not invited to the talks in 
Washington, formed their own republic in 1992 in their ethnic 
and historical territories. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

