<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   France, Germany, Poland Agree to Joint Military Exercises </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0703145694 Paris LE FIGARO in French 7 Mar 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> BR0703145694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE FIGARO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Xavier Gautier report: "French-German-Polish Maneuvers"] </F>
  [Excerpt] France, Poland, and Germany will move into the 
"practical" phase of their closer defense relationship this year. 
  When Polish Defense Minister Piotr Kolodziejczyk visited 
Paris last Thursday [3 March], the three states agreed to 
organize a joint exercise between chiefs of staff followed by 
ground maneuvers by army units from each country. 
  Reliable sources say that these could take place next 
autumn, 
in all likelihood in Mourmelon [France]. The Polish Army will 
place one unit -- probably a company -- at the disposal of the 
French-German brigade and the Eurocorps. The principle has been 
agreed on, even if, as a matter of procedure, the other members 
of the Eurocorps (in particular Spain and Belgium) have yet to 
be consulted. 
  These decisions were announced at the end of a working 
dinner 
-- the first of its kind -- at the Hotel de Brienne [Defense 
Ministry] last Thursday evening and attended by [Defense 
Ministers] Francois Leotard, Volker Ruehe, and Piotr 
Kolodziejczyk. During that meeting, an assessment was also made 
of the military cooperation between France and Poland over the 
past three years. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

