<H3> <TI>   Bundeswehr Inspector: NATO Needs New Command Structure </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0403105294 Hamburg DPA in German 0943 GMT 4 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0403105294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- In the view of Bundeswehr Inspector 
General Klaus Naumann, NATO will need to institute a new command 
and control structure in order to carry out peacemaking 
interventions in international conflicts. In an interview with 
Berlin "Deutschlandradio," Naumann said on Friday [4 March] that 
the alliance must also ask itself the fundamental question of 
whether it should assume a mandate in which it simply carries 
out orders on behalf of the United Nations or the CSCE, without 
being permitted to make its own decisions; or whether NATO 
should make decisions on a United Nations or CSCE mandate. 
  The question is also whether NATO will say of its own 
volition: Here is a security problem that we want to solve in 
the sphere of our interests in consensus between the 16 nations, 
and this is where we will prepare for the necessary action. 
Naumann emphasized that this issue requires a political answer. 
The inspector general reiterated his view that, in future, 
German units should also participate in such NATO operations. 

</TEXT>

