<H3> <TI>   Andreatta Comments on Greek Embargo Against FYROM </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0703112794 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1620 GMT 5 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0703112794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article:"Macedonia: Andreatta on Greek </F>
Embargo"] 
  [Text] Trieste, 5 Mar (ANSA) -- "I confirm that we tried to 
reduce the state of potential tension in the area, but for Italy 
and all the other members of the European Union [EU], Greece's 
action appeared to go beyond the necessary patience one needs in 
relations between neighbours," said Italian Foreign Minister 
Beniamino Andreatta today, answering a question on the Greek 
partial embargo on Macedonia [The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia--FYROM] after the Central European Initiative meeting 
here. 
  Andreatta again highlighted that the Greek decision -- in 
retaliation against Macedonia's declaration of independence 
under a name Greece says signals territorial ambitions on the 
northern Greek province of the same name -- was "a violation of 
precise European Union regulations." 
  All EU members except Greece have recognised the former 
Yugoslav republic as Macedonia. 
  He also stressed that "certain countries, including 
Macedonia" have suffered unduly from the embargo, and that it 
was necessary to "step in with some form of compensation." For 
this reason, Andreatta said, studies had begun on a road project 
linking Valona, Sofia and Istanbul. 
  Andreatta ended his reply to the Greece-Macedonia question 
by 
saying that "if Greece has put itself in an awkward position," 
it "cannot count on implicit European solidarity; our position 
is clear on that." 

</TEXT>

