<H3> <TI>   Minister Criticizes EU Expansion, Market Measures </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0403114094 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1546 GMT 3 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0403114094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "European Union: Expansion </F>
Strengthens Mark-Linked North, Costa Claims"] 
  [Text] Rome, 3 Mar (ANSA) -- The future expansion of the 
European Union [EU] to include Sweden, Finland and Austria is a 
"positive factor" but will increase the strength of those 
countries whose currencies are linked to the German mark, 
according to Italian Transport Minister Raffaele Costa. 
  "The area of influence under the mark has grown in a short 
time from sixty to one hundred million people, indirect 
influence is being tripled, and that's not the end of it because 
other countries in the area of the mark are knocking at the 
Union's door," Costa said Thursday [3 March], commenting the 
agreements reached Monday with the three northern states, which 
may join the EU in January 1995. 
  The prospects for Italy at the turn of the century will not 
be very bright, especially if Italy is unable "to gain 
considerable political and economic room in Europe and in the 
Mediterranean," Costa added. 
  "Europe itself, which inappropriately criticized us for our 
state-run overspending, never misses a chance to fatten itself 
with Franco-Prussian bureaucrats and to approve antifree market 
measures such as those on milk quotas," Costa claimed, referring 
to EU demands for reductions in milk production. 
  Italy, Costa asserted, must be able to negotiate and "fight" 
in a Europe which he described as "sometimes contradictory -- 
but always serious and careful with detail -- and conditioned, 
tomorrow more than today, by the Bundesbank." 

</TEXT>

