<F P=100> AUSTRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Debt, Trade, Joint Ventures With Russia Assessed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0403130594 Vienna DIE PRESSE in German 4 Mar 94 p 17 </F>
<F P=103> AU0403130594 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna DIE PRESSE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Erich Hoorn: "2 Billion Schillings Invested in </F>
Russia"] 
  [Text] Moscow/Vienna -- Russia's debt to Austria amounts 
to 67 billion schillings, while debts of about 15 billion 
schillings were rescheduled within the framework of the Paris 
Club (loans secured by the state) last year. It is still 
difficult for Austrian exporters to get credit guarantees from 
the Control Bank. They are only granted in special cases. 
  According to Guenter Richter, the Austrian trade delegate in 
Moscow, Austrian firms have so far established 475 joint 
ventures in Moscow, in which they have invested about 2 billion 
schillings. However, many of these enterprises only exist on 
paper. 
  In 1993 Austria's exports to Russia decreased by 9.6 percent 
to 6.2 billion schillings. This was a good result because 
Russia's total imports decreased by 30 percent. About 1,200 
Austrian firms deal directly or indirectly with the Russian 
market. The most important export items are consumer goods, 
equipment for the food industry, and supplies for the natural 
gas and oil industries. 
  Last year, Austria's imports increased by 2.3 percent to 7.7 
billion schillings. The most important import item is energy, 
whose share decreased from 90 percent to 70 percent. However, 
supplies of semifinished and finished products increased. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

