<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Cot Request for Additional Troops in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0403121894 Paris LE QUOTIDIEN DE PARIS in French 4 Mar 94 
p 14 </F>

<F P=103> BR0403121894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE QUOTIDIEN DE PARIS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Bosnia: General Cot Calls the </F>
United States to the Rescue"] 
  [Excerpt] Yasushi Akashi, special representative of the UN 
secretary general for the region, said that UNPROFOR [UN 
Protection Force] , which comprises around 14,000 troops in 
Bosnia, needs an additional 10,650 troops immediately, of which 
4,600 would be deployed in Sarajevo and 6,050 would monitor the 
enforcement of the Croatian-Muslim cease-fire in central and 
southern Bosnia. Mr. Akashi said that he was "deeply concerned 
about the reluctant and negative reply" from the international 
community to the reinforcement request for Bosnia. 
  Meanwhile, General Cot criticized NATO's attitude because of 
its readiness to send troops to Bosnia only after a 
comprehensive peace agreement has been reached. It is "a funny 
and not very brave decision," he said. "Anyone can change their 
minds and send troops to Bosnia tomorrow morning. I really 
would like the United States to send troops tomorrow morning," 
he added. "I need men immediately, but the nations which could 
dispatch troops immediately can be counted on the fingers of one 
hand," said Cot, who mentioned the United States, Great Britain, 
and France in this regard. 
  "Plans were drawn up by NATO providing for 100,000 troops. 
This was then reduced to 50,000. Today, I am asking for 10,000 
men. If one does not want everything that has been achieved in 
Sarajevo at the cost of incredible efforts to be completely 
undone, then those troops must come immediately," the French 
general stressed. "If they do not come rapidly, I am afraid 
that what has been won will be quickly lost." 

</TEXT>

