<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Sweden </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows 46 Percent Oppose EU Membership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0603214294 Stockholm Radio Sweden in Swedish 2100 GMT 6 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0603214294 </F>
<F P=104>  Stockholm Radio Sweden </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Swedish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Both the yes and no groupings have strengthened 
their positions after Sweden's agreement with the EU [European 
Union] was completed at the beginning of the week, according to 
a poll by SIFO [Swedish Institute for Public Opinion Polls] 
published in GOTEBORGS-POSTEN. The group opposing Swedish 
membership is still clearly the largest, and it increased by 2 
percent to 42 percent. The yes grouping increased by 3 percent 
to 35 percent. The number of undecided voters fell, 
consequently, and now totals 23 percent. 
  According to SIFO, different groups of voters have reacted 
very differently to the negotiation result. Upper-middle-age 
men are very satisfied, while younger voters have instead become 
more negative toward Swedish membership in the EU. 

</TEXT>

