<H3> <TI>   U.S. Seeks To Invalidate Greek CSCE Veto of FYROM </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0503090694 Athens ELEVTHEROTIPIA in Greek 4 Mar 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> NC0503090694 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ELEVTHEROTIPIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias and EU 
[European Union] Commissioner on Foreign Affairs Hans van den 
Broek will have a series of discussions on the issue of Skopje 
[The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia--FYROM] during their 
current joint tour of the Middle East. 
  These discussions will take place based on Wednesday's [2 
March] instruction from the EU commission to Van den Broek to 
continue his efforts to solve the dispute between Athens and 
Skopje. 
  The Greek Government spokesman described the EU's stance as 
"undoubtedly positive," and added that the Commission's stance 
gives weight to the political aspects of the issue, something 
the Greek Government has insisted on since the beginning. 
  However, a problem appeared yesterday in Prague during a 
high 
level CSCE meeting on the Skopje issue. 
  According to reports, the U.S. delegation, seconded by 
Britain and Turkey, insisted on describing the Greek measures 
against Skopje as a violation of human rights. In this way, 
they are seeking to invalidate the Greek veto of Skopje's CSCE 
membership. 
  As is known, the Greek Government has already made its 
intentions to retract the CSCE veto, provided Skopje meets the 
three Greek conditions for a resumption of the dialogue. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

