<H3> <TI>   Government Officials Comment on Deputies' Immunity </TI></H3>
<H4>   Demirel Answers Mitterrand Letter </H4>
<F P=102> TA0403162394 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1530 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0403162394 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, Mar. 4 (A.A.) -- President Suleyman Demirel 
sent a letter to French President Francois Mitterrand, saying 
that the objective of terror in Turkey was to divide the country 
and that like in other countries this was a grave crime in 
Turkey. 
  In his reply to the French president on Feb. 21, Demirel 
said 
that the judicial authorities will reach a conclusion on certain 
claims and proofs against certain deputies and that a legal 
process was in place, rather than an arbitrary one. 
  Demirel stressed that judgement in Turkey was independent 
and 
the right to defend oneself was limitless. 
  In his letter of Feb. 1, Mitterrand told Demirel that his 
government did not support the idea of an independent Kurdish 
state and had expressed some concerns on the removal of the 
immunity of some deputies. 
  Six members of the Democracy Party (DEP), one former DEP 
member and one fundementalist deputy were stripped from their 
immunity by parliament and were taken into custody today. 
  The DEP, with deputies from the southeast drew public 
reaction as they seemed to support the killing of innocent 
people by a separatist terrorist organization. 
  The organization is responsible of the death of more than 
10,800 people in Turkey in the last 10 years when it launched a 
bloody campaign against the Turkish state and its people. 
  Hasan Mezarci, then member of the fundamentalist Prosperity 
Party (RP), drew public anger and reaction when he led a group 
of 11 deputies in a motion to posthumously restore the honor of 
a group of anti-Kemalists who plotted to assassinate Mustafa 
Kemal Ataturk 70 years ago. 
  The motion sparked anger and prompted a pro-Kemalist rally 
led by Prime Minister Tansu Ciller Monday. Public anger reached 
a fever pitch after Mezarci made defamatory remarks about 
Ataturk, the founder of modern Turkey. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

