<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Expresses Condolences to Merkouri's Family </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0603170194 Athens ET-1 Television Network in Greek 1600 
GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0603170194 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ET-1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ladies and Gentlemen, [Culture Minister] Melina 
Merkouri is gone. Her death has touched the whole nation. At 
1545 today, this great Greek woman died at Memorial Hospital in 
New York. What an irony for this great Greek woman to die away 
from the country she loved. Exactly one month ago, she left 
Greece for some scheduled medical exams, saying: I am dressed 
in our blue and white national colors to give me courage, to 
come back again. 
  Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou said the following upon 
learning of Merkouri's death: Greece today mourns the death of 
Melina. She was a courageous fighter, great performer, and a 
wonderful person. Greece today mourns the death of the woman 
who, with her art and struggles, identified her name with Greece 
itself. All Greeks, who loved her and formed a particular 
relationship with her, are in mourning. It is a relationship 
that will outlast today's tragic moment. As prime minister, 
chairman of the PASOK [Panhellenic Socialist Movement], and a 
close friend, I bid farewell to Melina Merkouri with real 
sorrow. My wife and I express our sincere condolences to her 
partner Jules Dassin and to her family. 

</TEXT>

