<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel, Belarus' Kravchanka Discuss Reform, Aid </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0403205694 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE in German 
4 Mar 94 p 6 </F>

<F P=103> AU0403205694 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by "C. G.": "Kinkel Meets Kravchanka"] </F>
  [Text] Bonn, 3 Mar -- Foreign Minister Kinkel called on 
Belarus to continue economic and political reforms even after 
the election defeat of President Shushkyevich. At a meeting 
with Belarus Foreign Minister Kravchanka in Bonn on Thursday [3 
March], Kinkel said that Germany possibilities for providing 
Belarus with financial assistance had been exhausted. However, 
the faster privatization and reforms proceed, the easier it will 
be to successfully attract foreign private investment capital to 
Belarus. Kinkel and Kravchanka signed a cultural treaty that 
should facilitate the work of private organizations. A 
"memorandum of understanding" [preceding words in English] was 
signed on promoting cooperation in alleviating the effects of 
the accident at the Chernobyl nuclear power plant. It should 
eliminate bureaucratic obstacles in dealings between the two 
states and thus assist the work of private German relief 
organizations. Kravchanka said that only 1 percent of the 
territory of Belarus was unaffected by contamination resulting 
from the Chernobyl accident. The effects of the accident have 
caused suffering to 2.4 million Belarussians. 
  Kinkel praised Minsk's compliance with disarmament treaties. 
Like Kinkel, Kravchanka said he was in favor of an unlimited 
extension of the treaty on the nonproliferation of nuclear 
weapons until 1995. Kravchanka asked for technical and 
financial support for the destruction of tanks in accordance 
with the Vienna CSCE treaty on the scrapping of conventional 
weapons. Belarus must use its own financial resources to 
destroy foreign -- Soviet -- tanks and needs assistance. All 
formerly Soviet tanks that were withdrawn from abroad, including 
those that were stationed in the GDR, were brought to Belarus. 
Almost 2,000 tanks and 150 aircraft had to be destroyed, more 
than in the United States, Great Britain, and France. The 
destruction of missiles in line with START I nuclear disarmament 
is also costly. Kinkel promised that Germany would send experts 
to Russia to check what costs are involved. He could not, 
however, make any financial commitments. Kravchanka said that 
Belarus essentially took a "positive" view of the NATO offer of 
a Partnership for Peace, but had not made any official decision 
so far. Belarus would like to strengthen economic and political 
relations with Germany. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-18684 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu044_h_94005" </HT>


