<H3> <TI>   White Collar Union Settles Wage Dispute </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0503140794 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1229 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0503140794 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hanover (DDP/ADN) -- Following the pilot agreement 
between IG Metall [Industrial Trade Union of Metalworkers] and 
the employers, the German Salaried Employees Union (DAG), too, 
has now reached a wage settlement with the employers' 
association Gesamtmetall. After top-level talks with 
Gesamtmetall this morning in Hannover, DAG called off strikes 
scheduled for Monday [7 March] by its members in the engineering 
wage negotiating region of Lower Saxony, DAG spokesman Ingo 
Schwope said. 
  The negotiating parties, led by Gesamtmetall president 
Hans-Joachim Gottschol and DAG leader Roland Issen, have agreed 
on a 2-percent increase in wages and training grants from 1 
June, as well as settlements aimed at safeguarding jobs. The 
holiday bonus, suspended by the employers, will be reintroduced 
and backdated to 1 January 1994. Special payments such as the 
Christmas bonus will be subject to a one-off reduction of 10 
percent in 1994, it was reported. 

</TEXT>

