<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Threatens U.S. With GATT Reprisals </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0803090994 Paris AFP in English 0054 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0803090994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, March 8 (AFP) -- The European Union [EU] 
threatened here Monday [7 March] to retaliate against alleged 
deficiencies in U.S. tariff-reducing offers in the final days of 
the Uruguay Round of GATT trade talks. 
  EU foreign ministers said in a statement that the Union 
should reduce its tariff offers on items important to the United 
States in retaliation at deficient offers made by Washington. 
  They said the United States had made disappointing offers in 
tariff-cutting schedules that are to be included in the final 
Uruguay Round agreement of the General Agreement on Tariffs and 
Trade to be signed in Marrakesh on April 15. 
  An EU official, citing U.S. tariffs on trucks and copper, 
said the Union might in retaliation reduce its tariff-cutting 
offer in products such as nonferrous metals. 
  The ministers said such reprisals should target products 
where the United States supplied 90 percent of EU requirements, 
and should be carefully calibrated so that they could not be 
blamed for unravelling the Uruguay Round. 
  The meeting also expressed alarm at last week's decision by 
the United States to reactivate its Super 301 trade regulation 
to force open the Japanese market. 
  The statement said the trade measure would be carefully 
scrutinised to make sure it did not violate EU trade rights. 
  A spokesman for EU Trade Commissioner Leon Brittan quoted 
him 
as saying that Super 301 was viewed with concern as a unilateral 
trade reprisal that went against the GATT tide of multilateral 
dispute settlement. 
  French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe stressed France's demand 
that the effect on trade of environmental, social and monetary 
issues should be spotlighted at the Marrakesh conference, where 
a new World Trade Organisation is to be set up. 
  The French demand aims at preventing countries profiting 
from 
cut-price exports through poor environmental and social 
standards, and monetary manipulation. 
  There was some suport for establishing an environmental 
committee at Marrakesh. "But let's not cloud the Uruguay Round 
with other issues now," Brittan's spokesman said. 

</TEXT>

