<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Approaches `Major Crisis' Over Expansion </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0703215394 Paris AFP in English 2114 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0703215394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, March 7 (AFP) -- The European Union [EU] 
is approaching a major crisis in its row over voting procedures 
if it accepts new members, Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros 
Pangalos said here Monday [7 March]. 
  Pangalos, chairman of the EU's Council of Foreign Ministers, 
said they had failed to overcome a dispute over a change in the 
balance of power if Austria, Finland, Sweden and possibly Norway 
are admitted in 1995. 
  The issue is threatening to wreck the chances that the four 
countries will be able to join the Union. 
  Pangalos said he would turn the matter over to EU heads of 
state and government if the foreign ministers failed at another 
attempt to resolve the dispute on Tuesday. 
  Italy on Monday joined Britain and Spain in insisting that 
the entry of the three or four newcomers should not affect the 
ability of a small number of countries to block controversial 
decisions. 
  The Greek minister added that there had been no progress in 
a 
dispute between Norway and Spain which is blocking the 
Norwegians' entry into the Union. 
  Spain is trying to gain catch quotas for Norwegian cod as 
part of the price for Norway's membership of the EU, a price 
which Oslo is steadfastly refusing to pay. 
  The European Union agreed with Austria, Finland and Sweden 
last week on their terms of entry, a decision which will have 
little effect if the enlargement process is torpedoed by the 
voting quarrel. 

</TEXT>

