<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nordic Council Session Focuses on EU, Baltics, Russia </TI></H3>
<H4>   Finland Not To Mediate in Dispute </H4>
<F P=102> LD0703174094 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1700 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0703174094 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Finnish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Nordic countries have again urged the withdrawal 
of Russian troops from the Baltic countries. The Nordic prime 
ministers, meeting in Stockholm, thought it important that the 
Russian soldiers should withdraw from Estonia and Latvia by the 
end of August as Russia has promised. Prime Minister Esko Aho 
stressed that Finland will not offer to act a mediator in the 
dispute, even though Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin 
will be visiting Finland at the end of the week. According to 
Aho, it is important for Finland, however, to maintain contacts 
with both sides. 
  The prime ministers of the Baltic countries were also in 
Stockholm today. Estonian Prime Minister Mart Laar stressed 
that the Russian troops pose no direct military threat to 
Estonia, but the issues concern environmental problems and crime. 

</TEXT>

