<F P=100> BENELUX </F>
<F P=101> Belgium </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Indicates PS, VLD Losing Ground </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0703150394 Brussels DE MORGEN in Dutch 7 Mar 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> BR0703150394 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels DE MORGEN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed KvdB: "PS Plummeting, VLD Losing Much </F>
Ground; Agalev and Flemish Bloc Only Flemish Winners in February 
Poll"] 
  [Text] Brussels -- The PS [Walloon Socialist Party] is 
suffering very adverse effects from the continuous scandals 
which have been ravaging the government in recent months. The 
February poll, conducted by Dimarso on behalf of DE MORGEN, 
reveals that the Walloon Socialists only represent 30.1 percent 
of the French-speaking electorate, representing a 6-percent drop 
since December. 
  In Flanders, the VLD's [Flemish Liberals and Democrats] 
progress seems to have come to a standstill. Party leader 
Verhofstadt and his supporters lost 1.5 percent (down to 28.5 
percent), and are now at their lowest level since July 1993. 
Dimarso's monthly poll was conducted between 7 and 16 February 
among 1,000 Flemish, 1,000 Walloons, and 400 people from 
Brussels. There was a "no response" from 18 percent of those 
questioned. 
  In Flanders, the majority parties are not benefiting from 
the 
VLD's downturn. The CVP [Christian People's Party] remains 
practically at the same level (21.8 percent), while the SP 
[Flemish Socialist Party] has dropped from 18.3 to 17.6 percent. 
Even the Volksunie [People's Union] has fallen from 6.6 to 6.3 
percent, despite the strong European list it disclosed in 
February. 
  The winners are Agalev [Live Differently] (up 0.7 percent to 
11.3 percent), the Vlaams Blok [Flemish Bloc] (from 9.7 percent 
to 11.5 percent), and Rossem (from 2 to 2.4 percent). 
<H5>  Walloon Region </H5>
  In the Walloon region, the PSC [Social Christian Party] is 
the biggest winner. Deprez' party registered a 1.5 percent 
increase to 20.1 percent; the PRL [Liberal Reformation Party] 
climbed slightly to 23 percent (up 0.7 percent); and the Ecolo 
[Ecologists] jumped to 16.3 percent (up 0.9 percent). The 
category "others," which in addition to the FDF [French-Speaking 
Front] and some minor leftwing parties includes ultraright-wing 
parties, lost some ground (from 11.2 to 10.5 percent). 

</TEXT>

